    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Geraldo Perdomo** stands as our premier play with a 68.41 rating, bolstered significantly by his leadoff status and a favorable matchup against Martin. His ability to anchor the top of the order provides the best path to Runs and our scarcest commodity, Stolen Bases. Close behind is **Bryson Stott** (62.02), who benefits from favorable wind conditions and a solid platoon edge against E. Cabrera, pushing his efficiency well into the \"Strong\" category. While **Matt Chapman** (57.17) and **Luis Arraez** (54.16) face a tough test against Glasnow, their high-order positioning and the boost from Glasnow's slow delivery\u2014which increases the probability of stolen bases for our active lineup\u2014keep them firmly in the starting spots despite the elite opposing arm.\n\nOur bench strategy remains constrained by off-days for core producers like **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**, **Cal Raleigh**, and **Lawrence Butler**, leaving little room for maneuver. The most difficult decision rested on the final outfield spot; **Jung Hoo Lee** (51.45) ultimately edged out **Wenceel Perez** (45.20) and **Drew Gilbert** (43.24) by maximizing his platoon advantage. While **Wenceel Perez** benefits from a weaker pitcher in Sproat, his lower spot in the order hampered his scoring potential relative to the rest of the lineup. As a final risk assessment, keep a close eye on the Glasnow matchup; his elite status naturally suppresses our ceiling, meaning **Drew Gilbert** and **Jung Hoo Lee** are at high risk of failing to provide value if the opposition executes efficiently. We are operating with a lean lineup today, prioritizing high-contact floor play from **Luis Arraez** and **Gleyber Torres** to navigate the difficult pitching slate.",
